# Lymph Nodes

> Lymph nodes are **small bean-shaped lymphoid organs** (2–25 mm) located throughout the body along lymphatic vessels. They filter lymph, trap antigens, and coordinate adaptive immune responses. Clinically, lymphadenopathy is a key sign of infection, inflammation, or malignancy.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Lymphatic System]]
- Drain into: Thoracic duct (left body) or right lymphatic duct → venous system

## 🔬 Structure
| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| Capsule | Fibrous; sends trabeculae inward |
| Cortex | **B-cell zone**; primary (naïve B cells) and secondary follicles (germinal centres — active response) |
| Paracortex | **T-cell zone**; HEV (high endothelial venules) — lymphocyte entry from blood |
| Medulla | Medullary cords (plasma cells, macrophages) + medullary sinuses |
| Afferent lymphatics | Enter via capsule |
| Efferent lymphatic | Exits at hilum |

## 🗂️ Clinically Important Node Groups

### Head & Neck
| Group | Drains |
|-------|--------|
| Submandibular | Oral cavity, teeth, anterior tongue, lips |
| Cervical (superficial + deep) | Head, neck, thyroid, oesophagus |
| Preauricular | Scalp, pinna, conjunctiva |
| Posterior auricular | Posterior scalp |
| Occipital | Posterior scalp |

### Thorax
| Group | Drains |
|-------|--------|
| Hilar / mediastinal | [[Lungs]], [[Bronchi]], trachea |
| Paratracheal | Trachea, thyroid |

### Abdomen & Pelvis
| Group | Drains |
|-------|--------|
| Para-aortic (lumbar) | [[Kidney]], [[Ovaries]], [[Testes]], [[Uterus]] (fundus) |
| Mesenteric | Small intestine, large intestine |
| Coeliac | [[Liver]], [[Stomach]], [[Pancreas]], [[Spleen]] |

### Upper Limb
| Group | Drains |
|-------|--------|
| Axillary (5 groups) | Breast, upper limb, lateral thorax |
| Epitrochlear | Medial hand, little + ring fingers |

### Lower Limb
| Group | Drains |
|-------|--------|
| Superficial inguinal | Lower limb, perineum, anterior abdominal wall below umbilicus, **scrotal skin** + **vulva** |
| Deep inguinal | Glans penis, clitoris, deep structures |

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Lymphadenopathy** — generalised (systemic: EBV, HIV, lymphoma) vs. regional (local: infection, metastasis)
- **Virchow's node** — left supraclavicular; receives thoracic duct; Troisier's sign in gastric/abdominal malignancy
- **Sentinel node biopsy** — first node in drainage basin; breast cancer + melanoma staging
- **Mediastinal widening** — lymphoma, sarcoidosis, TB, lung cancer (hilar nodes)
- **Kikuchi disease** — cervical lymphadenitis in young women; self-limiting; exclude lupus

